`EXTRACT` the year from `SYSDATE` and then combine using string concatenation with your input and use `TO_DATE` to convert to a date:

```sql
CREATE PROCEDURE test (
  monthday     IN  VARCHAR2,
  desired_date OUT DATE
)
IS
BEGIN
  desired_date := TO_DATE( EXTRACT( YEAR FROM SYSDATE ) || monthday, &#39;YYYYMMDD&#39; );
END;
/
```

then:

```sql
DECLARE
  dt DATE;
BEGIN
  test( &#39;0101&#39;, dt );
  DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE( &#39;0101: &#39; || dt );
  
  test( &#39;1231&#39;, dt );
  DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE( &#39;1231: &#39; || dt );
  
  BEGIN
    test( &#39;9876&#39;, dt );
    DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE( &#39;9876: &#39; || dt );
  EXCEPTION
    WHEN OTHERS THEN
      DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE( &#39;9876: &#39; || SQLERRM );
  END;
END;
/
```

outputs:

&gt; &lt;pre&gt;
0101: 2019-01-01 00:00:00
1231: 2019-12-31 00:00:00
9876: ORA-01843: not a valid month
&gt; &lt;/pre&gt;

*db&lt;&gt;fiddle [here](https://dbfiddle.uk/?rdbms=oracle_11.2&amp;fiddle=163e4773f822051932b98777b931675f)*

If you want to return `NULL` for invalid inputs then:

```sql
CREATE PROCEDURE test (
  monthday     IN  VARCHAR2,
  desired_date OUT DATE
)
IS
BEGIN
  desired_date := TO_DATE( EXTRACT( YEAR FROM SYSDATE ) || monthday, &#39;YYYYMMDD&#39; );
EXCEPTION
  WHEN OTHERS THEN
    -- In general don&#39;t catch OTHERS but in this case the only exceptions
    -- are going to be from TO_DATE
    desired_date := NULL;
END;
/
```

*db&lt;&gt;fiddle [here](https://dbfiddle.uk/?rdbms=oracle_11.2&amp;fiddle=7a04fa1d6806405a74902ba6ad6eed0c)*

------------------

**Update**:

You could simplify the code (as suggested by [Aleksej](https://stackoverflow.com/a/58520521/1509264) and [William Robertson](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/58520050/how-to-split-a-varchar-in-half-in-sql-procedure/58520142?noredirect=1#comment103368970_58520142)) by not specifying the year value in `TO_DATE` and use the default which appears to be the current year; however this behaviour is not, obviously, documented in any Oracle documentation pages so I would also include inline documentation within the function so future developers reviewing your function know that you are deliberately using this behaviour:

```sql
CREATE PROCEDURE test (
  monthday     IN  VARCHAR2,
  desired_date OUT DATE
)
IS
BEGIN
  -- Assumes that TO_DATE will, when not specified, default the year to the
  -- current year and the time to midnight.
  desired_date := TO_DATE( monthday, &#39;MMDD&#39; );
END;
/
```

